    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-06-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-06-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="454"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d454">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.<gloss target="#t_BC1">BC</gloss>
                    Atomic/6–2746</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by Mr. <persName type="from">James E.
                            Doyle</persName>, Assistant to the Counselor</hi> (<persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Cohen</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Acheson</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="7" xml:id="d454fn7">The source text bears the following
                        handwritten addition by Mr. Doyle: “This refers to Moscow’s 2013 of June 27,
                        1946.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-06-27">June 27,
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I think the most important thing by far is that the current negotiations on the
                    UN Atomic Energy Commission should be held strictly to exploring the nature of
                    the problem of the control of atomic energy. This means that the discussions
                    should be directed to the functions of an international authority on atomic
                    energy. It seems to me unwise even to branch out to the enforcement problem now,
                    and clearly unwise to branch out from atomic energy to the entire field of
                    disarmament.</p>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_SPA1">SPA</gloss>’s views on the telegram (through Mr.
                    Blaisdell) are that the USSR has not in fact seized the moral leadership, that
                    inspection is probably not the “basic issue” presently, that the USSR has not
                    grasped the initiative, that the United States may not desire to agree to
                    “unhampered inspection of military establishments and means of production”, and
                    that the Embassy in Moscow may be unable to evaluate more than “the one vital
                    factor” to which it refers.</p>
            </div>
